{{italic title}}
'''''Les Butors et la Finette''''' is a 1917 play by French dramatist [[François Porché]]. 
Described as a "symbolical and allegorical drama", <ref name="Dickinson1937">{{cite book|last=Dickinson|first=Thomas Herbert|title=The theater in a changing Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fmpSAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=30 April 2012|year=1937|publisher=H. Holt and Company|page=217}}</ref> with "shocking realism", the play was hailed as the best French drama of World War I and one of its most original.<ref name="FranklinFuller1919">{{cite book|last1=Franklin|first1=Fabian|last2=Fuller|first2=Harold de Wolf|title=The Weekly review: devoted to the consideration of politics, of social and economic tendencies, of history, literature, and the arts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j0cgAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=30 April 2012|year=1919|publisher=The National Weekly Corporation|page=220}}</ref><ref name="Chandler1925">{{cite book|last=Chandler|first=Frank Wadleigh|title=The contemporary drama of France|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jOMUAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=30 April 2012|year=1925|publisher=Little, Brown, and Company}}</ref>

