==Notes== For this season, *[[Stephen Hendry]], despite having not had the best of seasons, regains the number one spot after nine years from second place. *[[Paul Hunter (snooker player)|Paul Hunter]] drops out of the top 32, down from number five to number 34 at the end of the [[Snooker season 2005/2006|2005/2006 season]],<ref>{{cite web|title=2005/6 Main Tour Two Year Rankings Updated 01/05/06 after 888.com World Championship|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/05-6twoyrrks.htm|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005051808/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Rankings/05-6twoyrrks.htm|archivedate=5 October 2008}}</ref> shortly before his death from [[neuroendocrine tumours]]. *[[Jimmy White]] drops out of the top 32 after his worst season to date, down from 8 to 34. *[[Alan McManus]] drops out of the top 16 after ten seasons, down from 12 to 19. *[[Ian McCulloch (snooker player)|Ian McCulloch]] drops out of the top 16 after one season, down from 16 to 25. *[[Anthony Hamilton (snooker player)|Anthony Hamilton]] re-enters the top 16 after gaining one place, from 17 to 16. *[[Barry Pinches]] drops out of the top 32, down from 18 to 33. *[[Allister Carter]] reaches the top 16 for the first time in his career, rising from 19th to 15th. *[[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]] enters the top 16, from number 27 to number 13. *[[John Parrott]] drops out of the top 32, down from 28 to 42. *[[Ryan Day]] officially enters the top 32, from 33 (just outside the top 32, although he replaced the suspended [[Quinten Hann]], officially in 22nd place at the time, during most of the season) to 17. *[[Stuart Bingham]] and [[Ding Junhui]] enter the top 32, from 37th to 24th and 62nd to 27th respectively. *[[Mark Selby]] and [[Joe Swail]] re-enter the top 32, from 38th to 28th and 40th to 30th respectively.
